            "audio": [
                {
                    "id": 814,
                    "name": "interview-weaver-01",
                    "file_name": "interview-weaver-01.mp3",
                    "human_readable_size": "48.2 MB",
                    "mime_type": "audio/mpeg",
                    "url": "https://files.vidstack.io/sprite-fight/audio.mp3",
                    "conversions": {},
                    "transcript": "Interviewer: Can you describe how you first learned to weave?\nParticipant: My grandmother taught me when I was seven years old. She sat me down at the small loom by the window and showed me how to pass the shuttle through the warp.\n\nInterviewer: Were there specific patterns your family used?\nParticipant: Yes, every family in the valley had its own arrangement of stripes and motifs. Ours used a red and ochre diamond that my great-grandmother brought from the mountains.\n\nInterviewer: How has the practice changed over the years?\nParticipant: Fewer people weave now. The young ones move to the cities for work, and the wool is harder to source. But a handful of us still meet each winter to share patterns and stories."
                }
            ],
            "document": [
                {
                    "id": 815,
                    "name": "field-notes-2021",
                    "file_name": "field-notes-2021.pdf",
                    "human_readable_size": "3.15 MB",
                    "mime_type": "application/pdf",
                    "url": "https://www.w3.org/WAI/ER/tests/xhtml/testfiles/resources/pdf/dummy.pdf",
                    "conversions": {},
                    "transcript": "Field notes, Kolari valley, July 2021.\n\nDay 1. Arrived in the morning, met with the head of the weaving cooperative. She introduced us to three weavers who had agreed to be recorded.\n\nDay 2. Recorded interview with weaver A in her workshop. Two looms active. Ambient noise from the nearby river is audible on the recording.\n\nDay 3. Photographed a series of finished textiles dating back to the 1960s. Wrote down notes on dye sources, warp counts, and regional variants."
                }
